Anti-Patterns Reference
1. Hardcoded text size
Wrong: android:textSize="16sp"

Why it fails: Bypasses the type scale entirely. Cannot be changed globally. Does not adapt to the app's font configuration or Material You type system.

Correct: android:textAppearance="?attr/textAppearanceBodyLarge"

2. Hardcoded text color
Wrong: android:textColor="#000000"

Why it fails: Hardcoded black text is invisible on dark backgrounds. Breaks dark mode completely and cannot be themed.

Correct: android:textColor="?attr/colorOnSurface"

3. Hardcoded background color
Wrong: android:background="@color/white"

Why it fails: White backgrounds break dark mode. Static colors do not adapt to the Material You dynamic color system.

Correct: android:background="?attr/colorSurface"

4. Deeply nested LinearLayouts
Wrong: LinearLayout inside LinearLayout inside LinearLayout to position one view.

Why it fails: Each nesting level multiplies measure and layout passes. Three levels of LinearLayout can mean 8x the measurement work compared to a flat layout. This causes dropped frames on mid-range devices.

Correct: Use a single ConstraintLayout and constrain the view directly to parent or sibling views. No nesting required.

5. layout_weight inside ScrollView
Wrong: android:layout_weight used on a child inside a LinearLayout that is inside a ScrollView or NestedScrollView.

Why it fails: ScrollView gives its child unlimited height. LinearLayout with layout_weight measures children against the parent height — which is infinite. The layout breaks or produces incorrect sizes.

Correct: Use fixed dimensions or switch to ConstraintLayout with constrained heights.

6. match_parent height on RecyclerView inside ScrollView
Wrong: RecyclerView with android:layout_height="match_parent" nested inside a ScrollView.

Why it fails: The RecyclerView cannot determine its height, so it renders all items at once without recycling. This defeats the purpose of RecyclerView and can cause out-of-memory errors on large lists.

Correct: Wrap the RecyclerView in a NestedScrollView and apply app:layout_behavior="@string/appbar_scrolling_view_behavior", or give the RecyclerView a fixed height, or redesign the screen to use the RecyclerView as the root scrollable container.

7. Left and Right directional attributes
Wrong: android:layout_marginLeft android:layout_marginRight android:paddingLeft android:layout_gravity="left"

Why it fails: Hardcoded left and right directions do not flip in RTL locales. Arabic, Hebrew, and other RTL users see a mirrored layout that does not adapt.

Correct: android:layout_marginStart android:layout_marginEnd android:paddingStart android:layout_gravity="start"

8. android:onClick in XML
Wrong: android:onClick="handleClick"

Why it fails: This requires a public method with that exact name on the hosting Activity or Fragment. It is impossible to unit test, creates tight coupling between XML and code, and causes a crash if the method is renamed or missing.

Correct: Set the click listener programmatically in Fragment.onViewCreated() or Activity.onCreate() using binding.btnAction.setOnClickListener { }.

9. Missing loading, empty, and error states
Wrong: A screen layout with only the success/content state defined.

Why it fails: Users see a blank screen during loading, no feedback when a list is empty, and a crash or frozen screen on errors. All four states must exist in the layout from the start.

Correct: Define all four states — Loading, Success, Empty, Error — in the layout. Use visibility toggling or ViewStub to show only the active state.

10. PNG icons via android:src
Wrong: android:src="@drawable/ic_share.png"

Why it fails: PNG bitmaps are blurry on high-DPI screens unless you provide mdpi, hdpi, xhdpi, xxhdpi, and xxxhdpi variants. This inflates APK size significantly. PNG icons cannot be tinted at runtime.

Correct: Use VectorDrawable (SVG-based) icons via app:srcCompat="@drawable/ic_share_24". They are resolution-independent, tintable, and a single file serves all densities.

11. CardView from androidx.cardview
Wrong: androidx.cardview.widget.CardView

Why it fails: This is the Material 2 component. It does not support Material 3 color tokens, shape theming, ripple behavior, or stroke. It will not adapt to the app theme.

Correct: com.google.android.material.card.MaterialCardView

12. Plain Button and plain EditText
Wrong: android.widget.Button android.widget.EditText

Why it fails: These are unstyled Android widgets. They do not apply Material theming, do not support M3 color roles or shape attributes, and produce inconsistent UI across devices and Android versions.

Correct: com.google.android.material.button.MaterialButton com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputLayout

com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputEditText
13. Hardcoded hint text
Wrong: android:hint="Enter your email address"

Why it fails: Hardcoded strings cannot be translated. The app will show English hint text in every locale, breaking localization for all non-English users.

Correct: android:hint="@string/hint_email"

14. Missing contentDescription on icon buttons
Wrong: An ImageButton or ImageView used as a button with no contentDescription set.

Why it fails: TalkBack announces the view as "unlabeled button". Users who rely on screen readers cannot discover what the button does. This also fails accessibility audits required for Play Store distribution in many regions.

Correct: Always set android:contentDescription to a string resource that describes the action performed by the button, not the icon itself. Write "Share recording" not "Share icon".

15. Touch target below 48dp
Wrong: An interactive element with layout_width="24dp" and layout_height="24dp" and no padding.

Why it fails: A 24dp tap area is impossible to hit accurately for users with motor difficulties, users on small screens, or anyone using the app with one hand. This fails WCAG 2.5.5 (Target Size) and Google's own accessibility guidelines.

Correct: Add padding to reach 48dp total: a 24dp icon with android:padding="12dp" achieves a 48dp tap area while keeping the visual icon at 24dp. Alternatively, use android:minWidth="48dp" and android:minHeight="48dp".
